In addition to calculating the gender ratio of authorship for each of the five corpora (including an assessment of the unsigned or unattributable works), I correlate gender with the basic categories of writing present in the corpus, to form more specific conclusions about the role of gender in corpus-building. Simple topic-modelling of the titles of eighteenth century works allows me to identify broad categories such as \cf2 plays, poetry, pamphlets, \cf3 novels, \cf2 songs, sermons, ephemera\cf3 , and so on. Titles in the eighteenth century are long, and served as advertisements, intentionally created to actively communicate this level of information about their works\'92 contents: although topic modelling of titles would not be sufficient in other centuries, it is remarkably effective here. Identifying the representation within each corpus of these categories of writing reveals a predictable preference for \'93literary\'94 forms such as novels and poetry in the smaller corpora.\
